Exercise 1: Air Pollution Study

Researchers wish to assess whether air pollution has a negative impact on well populated cities by investigating the cities mortality rates (per 100,000). It is generally accepted that mortality rates depend on a a number of factors including socioeconomic and environmental variables.

To assess whether air pollution has an effect on the mortality rate, we wish to determine whether measurements of pollutants such as nitrogen oxides and sulfur dioxide have an effect after accounting for well-known factors. The following code chunk loads in the data set and provides an overall summary graph. Precipitation is mean rainfall in inches. Education is median number of school years completed among adults and nonwhite is the percentage of the cities population that is nonwhite.

#load libraries
#load in the data set and provide an overall summary graph
library(Sleuth3)
library(GGally)
air<-ex1123
head(air)

A. Using the graph, provide commentary on what trends you see with the predictors and the mortality rate. Do any of them look nonlinear?

Trends:

  1. The higher educated seem to have lesser mortality
  2. Precipitation and mortality seems to be mostly linear
  3. NOX and SO2 with respect to mortality appears non-linear
  4. the higher the percentage of NonWhite mortality increases

B. Fit a regression model using all five predictors. Provide the residual diagnostics and comment on whether the assumptions look reasonable.

# mortality regression model
airmodel<-lm(Mort ~ Precip + Educ + NonWhite + NOX + SO2, data = air)
# diagnostic plots
par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(airmodel)

par(mfrow=c(1,1))

Discuss Assumptions:

  1. Residual vs Fitted Plot: The data is randomly scattered indicating equal variances
  2. Normal Q-Q Plot: The data mostly falls on the line indicating normality
  3. There doesn’t appear to be any data points with high leverage
  4. Independence: Since we don’t know how the data was selected, we will assume independence

C. Use the vif function within the car package to examine the VIFs. Are there any concerns for this particular study’s goals and research question? What if there were really high VIFs among Education, Nonwhite, and NOX? Would that change your answer?

Discuss VIFs Output:

  1. The independent variables that are being considered in this model have a VIF score under 5 which indicates no issues for multicollinearity
  2. The study’s goals is to understand if NOX and SO2 have an effect after accounting for well-known factors. Since there’s no strong relationship between these variables, the model can evaluate the significance of each variable in understanding if air pollution has an effect on mortality rate
  3. If there’s really high VIFs among Education, Nonwhite, and NOX then would need to understand the relationship between these variables to see if any can be eliminated for duplicate purposes or some other negative impact on the model that could effect results

Exercise 2: Predicting Fish Weights

This will be a quick exercise in writing a contrast. The fish data set includes weight, height, width, and 3 length measurements for seven different species of fish.

A quick exploration between the relationships between log(weight) and Length1 for the different species suggests that they potentially have different slopes.

# read fish file
# plot data
fish<-read.csv("Fish.csv",header=T,stringsAsFactors = T)

A. Fit a model so that individual intercepts and slopes are fitted for each species. Use the contrast framework to estimate the slope for the Smelt species. Provide a formal interpretation of this slope and include a 95 percent confidence interval. You do not need to provide a formal interpretation of the interval, just the slope value (point estimate).

  1. For 1 unit increase in Length1, the median log(Weight) will change by -94.41% holding all other variables fixed
# fish regression model
fishmodel = lm(log(Weight) ~ Length1 * Species, data = fish)

## Residual standard error: 0.2148 on 98 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.9794, Adjusted R-squared:  0.9779 
## F-statistic: 665.2 on 7 and 98 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16
# contrast maker
lm.contrast<-function(lmobj,contrast){
  if(is.matrix(contrast)==F) contrast<-matrix(contrast,nrow=1)
  if(ncol(contrast)!=length(coef(lmobj))) return("Error: Contrast length does not match the number of coefficients in linear model object.")
  estimates<-contrast %*% coef(lmobj)
  se<- sqrt(diag(contrast %*% vcov(lmobj) %*% t(contrast)))
  t.stat<-estimates/se
  p.val<-pt(-abs(t.stat),df=lmobj$df.residual)
  ci.l<-estimates-qt(.975,df=lmobj$df.residual)*se
  ci.u<-estimates+qt(.975,df=lmobj$df.residual)*se
  results<-data.frame(Estimates=estimates,SE=se,t.stat,p.val,Lower=ci.l,Upper=ci.u)
  return(results)
  }

# Smelt contrast:
smeltcontrast = c(0,1,0,0,0,0,0,1)
contrast.matrix<-rbind(smeltcontrast)
lm.contrast(fishmodel,contrast.matrix)
##               Estimates         SE   t.stat        p.val     Lower     Upper
## smeltcontrast 0.2635158 0.04896814 5.381374 2.523607e-07 0.1663402 0.3606915

Exercise 3

The following code simulates a data set that follows a trend that is a 4th degree polynomial. Below is a plot of the data along with residual plots from regression model.

set.seed(1234)
x<-runif(100,-6,6.5)
trend<- 2*x^4-2*x^3-50*x^2+100*x+2
y<-trend+rnorm(100,0,100)
mymodel<-lm(y~poly(x,2))

par(mfrow=c(1,3))
plot(x,y)
plot(mymodel$fitted.values,mymodel$residuals,ylab="Residuals",xlab="Fitted")
plot(x,mymodel$residuals,ylab="Resdiduals")

par(mfrow=c(1,1))

A. Using the graphics, explain to a layman why the current model being fitted is not a good fit to the data set.

  1. The residuals plot displays a trend which indicates the model needs to be adjusted so that the data points are randomly scattered around zero. When appropriately adjusted the output from the model will be more accurate.

B. To help the laymen better understand, repeat the graphics using different polynomial fits to illustrate what a better model fit would look.

#different polynomial fits
